The paper deals with the problem of inferring an appropriate DTD or XSD for a given collection of XML documents, which is a common problem in database systems (cs.DB). The approach taken involves learning deterministic regular expressions from sets of positive example words, which is a topic in machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also proposes a probabilistic algorithm for learning these regular expressions, which involves selecting the best expression based on a Minimum Description Length argument, which is a topic in information theory and machine learning (cs.LG). The algorithm is also empirically validated on real-world and synthetic data, which involves experimental design and data analysis (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the limitations of previous work and proposes a new method, which involves software engineering principles (cs.SE).
